February 01, 2018

KNN Overview

KNN is

A supervised method

An instance based learning method

  • does not produce a parameterized model

  • memorizies more than learns

  • K, an odd integer for classification

  • A 'lazy learner'

May be useful when building a parmeterized model is complicated

\(\mathbf {\widehat y} = f \left( \mathbf {X} , K \right)\)

Classification

  • Test data category is majority vote of categories among K nearest neighbors
  • A confusion matrix is used to test accuracy

Regression

  • Test data value is mean of K nearest neighbors' value
  • SSE, MSE, or RMSE is used to test accuracy

Applications

OCR and image classification

Recommendations

Patterns perhaps in genetic data

Classification relationships between explanatory and response variables are complicated, but classes are preferable distinct

The Curse of Dimensionality - As the number of features grow, the number of observations required for accuracy grows exponentially - Also note ISLR p 168

Distances

Nearest is measured as distance in feature space

Minkowski distances

Distance between the end points of vectors u and v

Row vectors in \(\bf X\) have been denoted as \(\bf x_i\)

Training and Testing Data Sets

Explanatory Variables

Must be numeric and scaled

For the \(j^{th}\) column (feature) of \(\bf X\), scale using either

\(X_j \leftarrow \frac{X_j - min\left(X_j\right) }{max\left(X_j\right) - min\left(X_j\right)}\)

\(X_j \leftarrow \frac{X_j - mean\left(X_j\right) }{std\:dev \left(X_j\right) }\)

And also \(\bf y\) similarly if numeric

Regression

Data generated from \(y= 5 \cdot x^2 - 2 \cdot x^4 + x + 500\) at .5 increments
Now what is the value of x = 2.7 ?

n = length(x) ; d = vector() 
for (i in 1:n)  {
  d[i] = abs(x[i]-xt)
}
Xk = data.frame(x,y,d)  
Xk = Xk[order(Xk$d),]
head(Xk)
##      x       y   d

## 4 -3.5 257.625 0.8

k = 1
plot(x,y, col = 'blue', pch = 16, main = paste('k = ',as.character(k)),  cex.main = 1) ; grid()
yt = mean(Xk[1:k,2]) ; points(xt,yt,col='red',pch=15)
abline(h = 0, col = 'gray') ; abline(v=0, col = 'gray')
for (i in 1:k) {
  points(Xk[i,1], Xk[i,2], col = 'red', pch = 1, cex = 1.5)
}

KNN Method from CLASS package

set.seed(101010)
pred = knn(Xtrain, Xtest, yTrain, k = 3)

t = table(actual = yTest, predicted = pred)
t
##       predicted
## actual   No  Yes
##    No  1080   15
##    Yes   67    3
accuracy = sum(diag(t)) / sum(t)
psr('accuracy rate',accuracy,4)
## [1] "accuracy rate 0.9296"
psr('error rate',1-accuracy,4)
## [1] "error rate 0.0704"

But the base accuracy rate of always choosing no is 94%

But what if the sales people contacted only those prospects that were predicted to buy ?

A key result of the experiment is leveraging the precision

predBuy = t[3] + t[4]
predBuy 
## [1] 18
salesCloseRate = t[4] / predBuy
psr('sales close rate', salesCloseRate, 4)
## [1] "sales close rate 0.1667"

So by calling on these prospects the close rate is much greater than of calling on random prospects !
